AllLife Bank Customer Segmentation - Problem Statement¶

Description¶

Context¶

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalized campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the bank poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customer queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help

Objective¶

To identify different segments in the existing customer, based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank, using clustering algorithms, and provide recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers.

Data Description¶

The data provided is of various customers of a bank and their financial attributes like credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customers have contacted the bank for any queries (including visiting the bank, online and through a call center).

Data Dictionary¶

  • Sl_No: Primary key of the records
  • Customer Key: Customer identification number
  • Average Credit Limit: Average credit limit of each customer for all credit cards
  • Total credit cards: Total number of credit cards possessed by the customer
  • Total visits bank: Total number of visits that customer made (yearly) personally to the bank
  • Total visits online: Total number of visits or online logins made by the customer (yearly)
  • Total calls made: Total number of calls made by the customer to the bank or its customer service department (yearly)

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

Kmeans Clustering¶

In [18]:
# To check for the appropriate number of K using the Elbow method
clusters = range(1, 10)
meanDistortions = []

for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(df_scaled)
    prediction = model.predict(df_scaled)
    distortion = (
        sum(np.min(cdist(df_scaled, model.cluster_centers_, "euclidean"), axis=1))
        / df_scaled.shape[0]
    )

    meanDistortions.append(distortion)

    print("Number of Clusters:", k, "\tAverage Distortion:", distortion)

plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, "bx-")
plt.xlabel("k")
plt.ylabel("Average Distortion")
plt.title("Selecting k with the Elbow Method", fontsize=20)

# To check for the appropriate number of K using the silhouette scores
sil_score = []
cluster_list = list(range(2, 10))
for n_clusters in cluster_list:
    clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters)
    preds = clusterer.fit_predict((df_scaled))

    score = silhouette_score(df_scaled, preds)
    sil_score.append(score)
    print("For n_clusters = {}, silhouette score is {}".format(n_clusters, score))

Hierarchical Clustering¶

In [28]:
# To get the cophenitic correlation of each pair of distance and linkage method

# list of distance metrics to apply on the data set
distance_metrics = ["euclidean", "chebyshev", "mahalanobis", "cityblock"]

# list of linkage methods to apply
linkage_method = ["single", "complete", "average", "centroid", "ward", "weighted"]
linkage_method_ = ["single", "complete", "average", "weighted"]

high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0, 0]

for dm in distance_metrics:
    if dm == "euclidean":
        for lm in linkage_method:
            Z = linkage(df_scaled, metric=dm, method=lm)
            c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(df_scaled))
            print(
                "Cophenetic correlation for {} distance and {} linkage is {}.".format(
                    dm.capitalize(), lm, c
                )
            )
            if high_cophenet_corr < c:
                high_cophenet_corr = c
                high_dm_lm[0] = dm
                high_dm_lm[1] = lm
    else:
        for lm in linkage_method_:
            Z = linkage(df_scaled, metric=dm, method=lm)
            c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(df_scaled))
            print(
                "Cophenetic correlation for {} distance and {} linkage is {}.".format(
                    dm.capitalize(), lm, c
                )
            )
            if high_cophenet_corr < c:
                high_cophenet_corr = c
                high_dm_lm[0] = dm
                high_dm_lm[1] = lm

Let's see the dendrograms for the different linkage methods.¶

In [30]:
# lists to save results of cophenetic correlation calculation
compare_cols = ["Linkage", "Cophenetic Coefficient"]

# to create a subplot image
fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(linkage_method), 1, figsize=(15, 30))

# We will enumerate through the list of linkage_method above
# For each linkage method, we will plot the dendrogram and calculate the cophenetic correlation
for i, method in enumerate(linkage_method):
    Z = linkage(df_scaled, metric="euclidean", method=method)

    dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i])
    axs[i].set_title(f"Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)")

    coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(df_scaled))
    axs[i].annotate(
        f"Cophenetic\nCorrelation\n{coph_corr:0.2f}",
        (0.80, 0.80),
        xycoords="axes fraction",
    )

Observations

  • The cophenetic correlation is highest for average and centroid linkage methods.
  • We will move ahead with average linkage.
  • 3 appears to be the appropriate number of clusters from the dendrogram for average linkage.

**Cluster 0

  • The clients here occupies the middle class in terms of Average credit limit(between 12,500-55,000) and total credit cards possessed(between 4-6) but reach the bank mostly by visiting personally(3-5 times yearly). They constitute the bulk of the bank's clients as 386 are in this cluster.

**Cluster 1

  • The clients in the group are the ones who enjoy the highest average credit limit(between 80,000-200,000) and have the highest number of credit cards(between 8-10) but mostly reach the bank through the online channels(between (6-15 times yearly). They however are the least in number totalling 50.

**Cluster 2

  • The clients here generally have the lowest average credit limit(with most of them having credit limit below 25,000), lowest number of credit cards(mostly below 4) and mostly reach the bank through calls(5-10 times yearly). 224 clients are in this cluster.

K-means vs Hierarchical Clustering¶

  • The two techniques suggest the same number of clusters (i.e. 3) that exist in the dataset.
  • K-means clustering actually takes lesser time to compute than Hierarchical Clustering,
  • Comparing the clusters obtained through K-Means and Hierarchical Clustering techniques, except the Cluster name that differs, they are very similar in profile. 
    * Cluster 0 under K-Means Clustering is the same as Cluster 2 under Hierarchical Clustering. They also contain the same number of observations(224)
* Cluster 1 under K-Means Clustering is the same as Cluster 0 under Hierarchical Clustering containing the same number of observations(386)
* Cluster 2 under K-Means Clustering is the same as Cluster 1 under Hierarchical Clustering containing the same number of observations(50)

Summary of Insights¶

The credit card customers of Alllife Bank can be classified into three distinct segments and there segments profiles in no particular order is displayed below:

** First Segment

  • The clients with low credit limit(with most of them having credit limit below 25,000), low number of credit cards(mostly below 4) and mostly reach the bank through calls. 224 clients are in this segment.

** Second Segment

  • The clients with average credit limit(between 12,500-55,000), average number credit cards, and reach the bank mostly by visiting personally. They constitute the bulk of the bank's credit card clients as 386 are in this segment.

** Third Segment

  • The clients with high credit limit(between 80,000-200,000), high number of credit cards, and mostly reach the bank through the online channels. They however are the least in number totalling 50.

Recommendations¶

** Whenever the marketing team runs personalized campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers, such campaigns have to be pitched through the three channels of reaching the bank(i.e personal visit, online channel, and call centers) so as to reach all the three segments of the customers identified. However, there should be special focus on customers in second segment identified under 'Insights' above as they constitute the bulk of the bank's credit card customers. Therefore positioning such campaigns more during customer's personal visitations to the bank will likely yield better result.

** Secondly, for the customers' perception of the bank's support services to change positively, services need to be improved upon at all service points especially when interfacing with customers on personal visits to the bank. The bank may need to increase their manpower at the in-branch customer service desks and/or train/re-train the staff on how to deliver excellent customer services.
